{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"925b3fe0-f4a6-41c7-8411-7fb948c08313","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` only controls the **Shell's** safe-area padding. The actual system chrome (status bar, nav bar) still reserves space unless you explicitly tell the platform to draw behind it. You need two things:\n\n### 1. iOS — disable safe-area insets on the page\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n### 2. Android — enable edge-to-edge rendering\n\nIn `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    // Draw behind system bars\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n\n    // Make system bars transparent\n    Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n}\n```\n\n> **Note:** On Android 15+ (API 35), edge-to-edge is enforced automatically, but you still need `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` on older API levels.\n\n### 3. Make the Image fill the space\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nThe combination of **platform-level edge-to-edge** + **`UseSafeArea=\"False\"`** on iOS + a fill-mode `Image` will get you truly edge-to-edge rendering.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"38b08718-08ad-493a-8a85-31710a1267dc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. The key issue is that `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on `ContentPage` isn't sufficient by itself. In .NET MAUI (especially with .NET 8+), you need to also handle platform-specific configuration to make content render behind system bars.\n\nLet me think about what's needed:\n\n1. **`IgnoreSafeArea`** - On the layout/view level, you can use `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the view itself.\n\n\n2. For Android, I need to disable the system window insets by calling the appropriate platform API to make the window extend behind the system bars, and ensure the status bar and navigation bar are transparent. On iOS, I'll need to use the safe area ignore settings at both the page and view level.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the user might be using Shell, which has its own `SafeAreaEdges` property that controls which edges apply safe area padding. For a full edge-to-edge solution across both platforms, the approach is to disable safe area on iOS using the platform-specific page property, and on Android to configure the window to extend behind system bars with transparent bars. For iOS I need to use the platform-specific `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` property, while on Android the solution involves enabling edge-to-edge rendering at the platform level with `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` and making the system bars transparent. The Image itself should fill its parent container with `AspectFill` to properly extend to the edges. The user's `SafeAreaEdges` property might not be the standard approach here, so I should clarify the correct platform-specific implementations.","outputTokens":1415,"requestId":"0438:FA277:13234D9:1581E85:6A027CC4"},"id":"7d31c226-08e4-450f-8c34-e10e3337af12","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:05:36.569Z","parentId":"6a5c2664-f6c3-4394-99cc-d0446072aea3"}
